# AnalogWeightRotations — Project Overview

## Research Goal

This project extends **SpinQuant**-style learned weight rotations from digital quantization to **Analog In-Memory Compute (AIMC)** hardware accuracy. The mathematical mechanism is identical — rotating `W → W R^T` and `x → Rx` is an exact equivalence that preserves `y = Wx` in float — but the objective is fundamentally different.

**SpinQuant** optimizes rotations to minimize outliers / kurtosis in weights and activations, which reduces rounding error in INT4/INT8 quantization. This project replaces that loss function with a **multi-objective analog hardware loss** that accounts for the distinct failure modes of crossbar arrays: IR drop, conductance noise, and ADC/DAC quantization. The goal is to find rotation matrices that make weights "AIMC-friendly" without retraining.

The subject model is **GPT-2 small** (Hugging Face), focused on MLP layers. This may expand to larger models.

---

## What SpinQuant Does (our starting point)

SpinQuant (Meta, 2024) is a post-training quantization technique that learns optimal rotation matrices via **Cayley SGD on the Stiefel manifold** (the space of orthogonal matrices):

- Applies a single `R1` to the hidden dimension and per-head `R2` matrices to attention projections
- Initializes from a random Hadamard matrix
- Optimizes `R1`, `R2` to minimize quantization loss (kurtosis / outlier reduction) on a small calibration set
- Random rotations have high variance (up to 13pt accuracy swing) — learning fixes this

**Our modification:** swap or augment the quantization loss with an analog hardware loss. The rotation search engine (Cayley SGD / Stiefel manifold) can remain largely the same; the loss surface changes.

Reference: [`facebookresearch/SpinQuant`](https://github.com/facebookresearch/SpinQuant)

---

## AIMC Non-Idealities We Target

| Non-ideality | Description |
|---|---|
| **IR Drop** | Voltage loss along resistive wires; creates a spatial gradient — weights far from ADCs are more degraded |
| **Conductance Noise** | Physical noise on programmed conductance values (analog weight noise) |
| **Quantization** | ADC/DAC precision limits on both weights and activations |
| **Full PCM** | Phase-change memory model capturing all of the above together |

Traditional mitigation is **Hardware-Aware Training (HAT)** — retraining with simulated noise in the loop. This project aims to replace or reduce that with a cheap post-training rotation pass.

