## Tech Stack

| Layer | Tool |
|---|---|
| ML framework | PyTorch + Transformers (HuggingFace GPT-2) |
| Analog simulation | `aihwkit-gpu` (IBM Analog AI Hardware Kit) |
| Rotation optimization | Cayley SGD / Stiefel manifold (SpinQuant-style) |
| Experiment tracking | Weights & Biases (`wandb`) |
| Runtime | Docker container (`aimc-docker/`) + Conda env `aihwkit`, Python 3.11 |
| Analysis | Jupyter (`experiments/`) |

**Everything runs inside the Docker container.** To enter: build from `aimc-docker/Dockerfile`, then `docker run` with GPU access and the repo mounted at `/workspace`. All `python` commands below assume the `aihwkit` Conda env: `conda run -n aihwkit python ...`

---

## File Map

```
src/                          ← reusable, modular library — all new components go here
  baseline_forward.py         # Full GPT-2 forward pass with W&B logging and layer hooks
  rotation_utils.py           # Orthogonal / Hadamard rotation math (pure functions)
  apply_rotation.py           # Apply rotation to a layer; inverse sanity check vs baseline
  wandb_config.py             # Shared W&B project/entity defaults
  [loss.py]                   # (planned) Multi-objective analog hardware loss functions
  [optimizer.py]              # (planned) Stiefel manifold / Cayley SGD rotation search
  [tile_analysis.py]          # (planned) Per-tile failure diagnostics

experiments/
  rotation_experiments.ipynb  # Interactive exploration notebook

1layertests/
  explore_rotations.py        # Single-layer tests: rotation types × analog HW configs
  plot_results.py             # Visualizes W&B results tables
  wandb/                      # Cached W&B run artifacts (logs, config, result tables)

aimc-docker/
  Dockerfile                  # CUDA 12.8 base, Conda env with aihwkit-gpu, PyTorch, Jupyter
  smoke_test.py               # Sanity-check for Docker image
```

### `src/` Modularity Principle

`src/` is the shared library. Every reusable component — loss functions, rotation types, optimizers, hardware configs, evaluation metrics — belongs here as a standalone importable module. Scripts in `1layertests/` and `experiments/` import from `src/`; they do not re-implement logic. When adding new functionality, place it in `src/` first, then call it from the experiment script.

